{{Unreferenced|date=August 28, 2017}} '''Shikinen-sai''' (式年祭) refers to religious rituals performed at fixed intervals, often seen in the festivals of [[Shinto shrines]] and ancestral worship ceremonies.
Some shrines with significant historical lineage conduct rituals at predetermined intervals. For instance, at {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, grand {{ill|Shinkō-sai|ja|神幸祭|12=draft|12=draft}} ceremonies are held every 12 years during the [[Year of the Horse]]. Similarly, at {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, the well-known {{ill|Onbashira Festival|ja|御柱祭|12=draft|12=draft}} takes place every seven years (counting the year of the festival as the first year, making the actual interval six years) during the [[Year of the Tiger]] or [[Year of the Monkey]]. These festivals are often larger and more emphasized than the annual {{ill|Reisai|ja|例祭|12=draft|12=draft}} and hold a higher degree of significance.
In some cases, shrines reconstruct their buildings at fixed intervals as part of their rituals. This reconstruction is considered an integral part of the religious ceremonies and can be categorized as a type of Shikinen-sai. The most famous example is the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Jingū Shikinen Sengū|lt=Shikinen Sengū|ja|神宮式年遷宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, where all the shrine buildings are reconstructed every 20 years in a grand ceremony. Another example is the Onbashira Festival of Suwa Taisha, which includes elements of shrine rebuilding and can also be regarded as a form of Shikinen Sengū. Additionally, Shikinen-sai are not exclusive to grand shrines; local community shrines ({{ill|Ujigami|ja|氏神|12=draft|12=draft}}) may also conduct these rituals based on their unique traditions and historical significance.
In ancestral worship, ceremonies are also performed at specific intervals. Commonly observed in [[Buddhist]] practices, these ceremonies, known as {{ill|Nenki|ja|年忌|12=draft|12=draft}}, occur on particular years such as the first anniversary, third, seventh, thirteenth, seventeenth, and twenty-third anniversaries, among others. These rituals differ from routine ceremonies and hold special significance.
In {{ill|Imperial Household|ja|宮中祭祀|12=draft|12=draft}} rites, Shikinen-sai are regulated for intervals of 3, 5, 10, 20, 30, 40, and 50 years, and subsequently every 100 years. These rituals, related to ancestral worship, include major and minor ceremonies performed in the Shinto style.
Shrines dedicated to historical figures, such as {{ill|Nikkō Tōshō-gū|ja|日光東照宮|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kitano Tenman-gū|ja|北野天満宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, hold grand festivals every 50 years. These ceremonies could be seen as a fusion of ancestral worship and Shinto rituals.
== Major Shikinen-sai == * {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: Funamatsuri * {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Shinkō-sai|ja|神幸祭|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Onbashira Festival|ja|御柱祭|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Jingū Shikinen Sengū|lt=Shikinen Sengū|ja|神宮式年遷宮|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Kitano Tenman-gū|ja|北野天満宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: Grand Manto Festival * {{ill|Nikkō Tōshō-gū|ja|日光東照宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: Shikinen-sai * {{ill|Togakushi Shrine|ja|戸隠神社|12=draft|12=draft}}: Grand Shikinen Festival * {{ill|Kashii Shrine|ja|香椎宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: Temporary Hōhei Festival * {{ill|Usa Shrine|ja|宇佐神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}: Temporary Hōhei Festival
=== Shikinen-sai in Imperial Household Rites === ; Grand Ceremonies * Shikinen-sai for the last three generations of emperors * Shikinen-sai for previous empresses * Shikinen-sai for empresses who are the imperial mothers ; Minor Ceremonies * Shikinen-sai for emperors from Emperor Suizei to the fourth generation prior
{{Shinto-stub}}
